## Handling Deeply Nested Reads with Defaults

You want to read a field three layers deep, but any layer might be missing. Rather than nest three `if` checks, write a helper that walks a path and returns a default on failure.

```scheme
;; Read a deeply nested field, return a default if any layer is missing.
(define record
  '((user . ((profile . ((address . ((city . \"Tokyo\")))))))))

(define (safe-get-nested record path default)
  (if (null? path)
      record
      (let ((field (car path))
            (rest (cdr path)))
        (let ((value (json/get record field)))
          (if (equal? value 'nan)
              default
              (safe-get-nested value rest default))))))

(safe-get-nested record '(\"user\" \"profile\" \"address\" \"city\") \"unknown\")
;; => \"Tokyo\"

(safe-get-nested record '(\"user\" \"profile\" \"phone\") \"unknown\")
;; => \"unknown\"
```

First call succeeds—four layers deep. Second call hits `'nan` at `phone`, returns `\"unknown\"`. This is recursion + ESCAPE: walk the path until you hit bottom or failure.

