## Recursive Transformation of Nested Structures

Sometimes a record contains nested lists of records—a tree. You want to transform each node. Write a recursive function that walks the tree, applying a transformation at each level.

```scheme
;; Recursively add a 'level field to each node in a nested tree.
(define tree
  '((name . \"root\")
    (children . (((name . \"child1\")
                  (children . (((name . \"grandchild1\"))
                               ((name . \"grandchild2\")))))
                 ((name . \"child2\"))))))

(define (add-level node level)
  (let ((node-with-level (json/set node \"level\" level))
        (children (json/get node \"children\")))
    (if (equal? children 'nan)
        node-with-level
        (json/set node-with-level \"children\"
                  (map (lambda (child) (add-level child (+ level 1)))
                       children)))))

(add-level tree 0)
;; => ((name . \"root\")
;;     (level . 0)
;;     (children . (((name . \"child1\")
;;                   (level . 1)
;;                   (children . (((name . \"grandchild1\") (level . 2))
;;                                ((name . \"grandchild2\") (level . 2)))))
;;                  ((name . \"child2\") (level . 1)))))
```

Each node got a `level` field. Recursion walked the tree, `map` handled the children. This is deep recursion + transformation—hard, but clean.

