## Building a JSON Response for an HTTP Endpoint

You have a list of products; you want to return a JSON-like structure suitable for an HTTP response—a top-level object with a `\"data\"` field containing the list, a `\"count\"` field, and a `\"status\"` field.

```scheme
;; Build a JSON response wrapping a list of products.
(define products
  (list
   '((id . \"X1\") (name . \"Scarf\") (price . 1500))
   '((id . \"X2\") (name . \"Gloves\") (price . 1200))))

(define count (length products))

(define response
  (list
   (cons 'status \"ok\")
   (cons 'count count)
   (cons 'data products)))

response
;; => ((status . \"ok\")
;;     (count . 2)
;;     (data . (((id . \"X1\") (name . \"Scarf\") (price . 1500))
;;              ((id . \"X2\") (name . \"Gloves\") (price . 1200)))))
```

Three fields, one alist. You could serialize this with `json/encode` (if it existed) or pass it to a wired verb that expects a map. The shape is what matters—metadata + payload.

